The sum converges for $baseint=2$ and diverges for $baseint \geq 3$.
We first consider $baseint \geq 3$. Suppose the sum converges; then the fact that $funcmap(indexval)= indexval\, funcmap(digitnum)$ whenever $baseint^{digitnum-1}\leq indexval \leq baseint^{digitnum}-1$ yields
\begin{equation} \label{a6eq1}
\sum_{indexval=1}^\infty \frac{1}{funcmap(indexval)}
= \sum_{digitnum=1}^\infty \frac{1}{funcmap(digitnum)} \sum_{indexval=baseint^{digitnum-1}}^{baseint^{digitnum}-1} \frac{1}{indexval}.
\end{equation}
However, by comparing the integral of $1/realvar$ with a Riemann sum,
we see that
\begin{align*}
\sum_{indexval=baseint^{digitnum-1}}^{baseint^{digitnum}-1} \frac{1}{indexval}
&> \int_{baseint^{digitnum-1}}^{baseint^{digitnum}} \frac{\mathrm{d}realvar}{realvar} \\
&= \log (baseint^{digitnum}) - \log (baseint^{digitnum-1}) = \log baseint,
\end{align*}
where $\log$ denotes the natural logarithm. Thus \eqref{a6eq1} yields
\[
\sum_{indexval=1}^\infty \frac{1}{funcmap(indexval)}
> (\log baseint) \sum_{indexval=1}^\infty \frac{1}{funcmap(indexval)},
\]
a contradiction since $\log baseint > 1$ for $baseint \geq 3$. Therefore the
sum diverges.

For $baseint=2$, we have a slightly different identity because $funcmap(2) \neq 2\, funcmap(2)$. Instead, for any positive integer $iteridx$, we have
\begin{equation} \label{a6eq2}
\sum_{indexval=1}^{2^{iteridx}-1} \frac{1}{funcmap(indexval)}
= 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} +
\sum_{digitnum=3}^{iteridx} \frac{1}{funcmap(digitnum)} \sum_{indexval=2^{digitnum-1}}^{2^{digitnum}-1} \frac{1}{indexval}.
\end{equation}
Again comparing an integral to a Riemann sum, we see that for $digitnum \geq 3$,
\begin{align*}
\sum_{indexval=2^{digitnum-1}}^{2^{digitnum}-1} \frac{1}{indexval}
&< \frac{1}{2^{digitnum-1}} - \frac{1}{2^{digitnum}} + \int_{2^{digitnum-1}}^{2^{digitnum}} \frac{\mathrm{d}realvar}{realvar} \\
&= \frac{1}{2^{digitnum}} + \log 2 \\
&\leq \frac{1}{8} + \log 2 < 0.125 + 0.7 < 1.
\end{align*}
Put $boundval = \frac{1}{8} + \log 2$ and $limupper = 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6(1-boundval)}$. Then we can prove that $\sum_{indexval=1}^{2^{iteridx}-1} \frac{1}{funcmap(indexval)} < limupper$ for all $iteridx \geq 2$ by induction on $iteridx$. The case $iteridx = 2$ is clear. For the induction, note that by \eqref{a6eq2},
\begin{align*}
\sum_{indexval=1}^{2^{iteridx}-1} \frac{1}{funcmap(indexval)}
&< 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} + boundval \sum_{digitnum=3}^{iteridx} \frac{1}{funcmap(digitnum)} \\
&< 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} + boundval \frac{1}{6(1-boundval)} \\
&= 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6(1-boundval)} = limupper,
\end{align*}
as desired. We conclude that $\sum_{indexval=1}^\infty \frac{1}{funcmap(indexval)}$
converges to a limit less than or equal to $limupper$.

Note: the above argument proves that the sum for $baseint=2$ is at most $limupper < 2.417$. One can also obtain a lower bound by the same technique, namely $1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6(1 - boundval')}$ with $boundval' = \log 2$. This bound exceeds $2.043$. (By contrast, summing the first 100000 terms of the series only yields a lower bound of $1.906$.) Repeating the same arguments with $digitnum \geq 4$ as the cutoff yields the upper bound $2.185$ and the lower bound $2.079$.}

