The sum converges for $tornadoes=2$ and diverges for $tornadoes \geq 3$.
We first consider $tornadoes \geq 3$. Suppose the sum converges;
then the fact
that $quasarbeam(umbrella) = umbrella \, quasarbeam(lighthouse)$ whenever $tornadoes^{lighthouse-1} \leq umbrella \leq tornadoes^{lighthouse} - 1$ yields
\begin{equation} \label{a6eq1}
\sum_{umbrella=1}^\infty \frac{1}{quasarbeam(umbrella)}
= \sum_{lighthouse=1}^\infty \frac{1}{quasarbeam(lighthouse)} \sum_{umbrella=tornadoes^{lighthouse-1}}^{tornadoes^{lighthouse} - 1} \frac{1}{umbrella}.
\end{equation}
However, by comparing the integral of $1/waterfall$ with a Riemann sum,
we see that
\begin{align*}
\sum_{umbrella=tornadoes^{lighthouse-1}}^{tornadoes^{lighthouse} - 1} \frac{1}{umbrella}
&> \int_{tornadoes^{lighthouse-1}}^{tornadoes^{lighthouse}} \frac{d\,waterfall}{waterfall} \\
&= \log (tornadoes^{lighthouse}) - \log (tornadoes^{lighthouse-1}) = \log tornadoes,
\end{align*}
where $\log$ denotes the natural logarithm. Thus \eqref{a6eq1} yields
\[
\sum_{umbrella=1}^\infty \frac{1}{quasarbeam(umbrella)}
> (\log tornadoes) \sum_{umbrella=1}^\infty \frac{1}{quasarbeam(umbrella)},
\]
a contradiction since $\log tornadoes > 1$ for $tornadoes \geq 3$. Therefore the
sum diverges.

For $tornadoes=2$, we have a slightly different identity because $quasarbeam(2) \neq
2 \, quasarbeam(2)$. Instead, for any positive integer $cinnamon$, we have
\begin{equation} \label{a6eq2}
\sum_{umbrella=1}^{2^{cinnamon}-1} \frac{1}{quasarbeam(umbrella)}
= 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} +
\sum_{lighthouse=3}^{cinnamon} \frac{1}{quasarbeam(lighthouse)} \sum_{umbrella=2^{lighthouse-1}}^{2^{lighthouse} - 1} \frac{1}{umbrella}.
\end{equation}
Again comparing an integral to a Riemann sum, we see that for $lighthouse\geq 3$,
\begin{align*}
\sum_{umbrella=2^{lighthouse-1}}^{2^{lighthouse} - 1} \frac{1}{umbrella} &<
\frac{1}{2^{lighthouse-1}} - \frac{1}{2^{lighthouse}} + \int_{2^{lighthouse-1}}^{2^{lighthouse}} \frac{d\,waterfall}{waterfall}
\\
&= \frac{1}{2^{lighthouse}} + \log 2 \\
&\leq \frac{1}{8} + \log 2 < 0.125 + 0.7 < 1.
\end{align*}
Put $sandstone = \frac{1}{8} + \log 2$ and $jellyfish = 1+\frac{1}{2} +
\frac{1}{6(1-sandstone)}$. Then we can prove that $\sum_{umbrella=1}^{2^{cinnamon}-1}
\frac{1}{quasarbeam(umbrella)} < jellyfish$ for all $cinnamon \geq 2$ by induction on $cinnamon$. The case
$cinnamon=2$ is clear. For the induction, note that by \eqref{a6eq2},
\begin{align*}
\sum_{umbrella=1}^{2^{cinnamon}-1} \frac{1}{quasarbeam(umbrella)}
&< 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} + sandstone \sum_{lighthouse=3}^{cinnamon} \frac{1}{quasarbeam(lighthouse)} \\
&< 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} + sandstone \frac{1}{6(1-sandstone)} \\
&= 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6(1-sandstone)} = jellyfish,
\end{align*}
as desired. We conclude that $\sum_{umbrella=1}^\infty \frac{1}{quasarbeam(umbrella)}$
converges to a limit less than or equal to $jellyfish$.

Note: the above argument proves that the sum for $tornadoes=2$ is at most
$jellyfish < 2.417$. One can also obtain a lower bound by the same technique,
namely $1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6(1 - sandstone')} $ with $sandstone' = \log 2$.
This bound exceeds $2.043$. (By contrast, summing the first 100000 terms of
the series only yields a lower bound of $1.906$.)
Repeating the same arguments with $lighthouse \geq 4$
as the cutoff yields the upper bound $2.185$ and the lower bound $2.079$.

